leukocytes in tissues","Reduced apoptosis of circulating neutrophils","Primary proliferation of white blood cells in circulation","Decreased margination of neutrophils along vessel walls","Accelerated release of granulocytes from bone marrow"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has an acute bacterial infection (likely pyelonephritis) with leukocytosis characterized by neutrophilia with a shift to the left (increased band forms). The primary mechanism responsible for this acute leukocytosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccelerated release of granulocytes from bone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs due to cytokines such as tumour necrosis factor (TNF) and interleukin-1 (IL-1) that are released during inflammation. This accelerated release results in both mature and immature neutrophils entering the circulation, creating the characteristic \u0027shift to the left\u0027 seen in acute infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased sequestration of leukocytes in tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - During inflammation, there is actually increased rather than decreased sequestration of leukocytes in infected tissues.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced apoptosis of circulating neutrophils\u003C/strong\u003E - While inflammatory mediators can prolong neutrophil survival, this is not the primary mechanism of acute leukocytosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary proliferation of white blood cells in circulation\u003C/strong\u003E - White blood cells do not proliferate in the circulation; proliferation occurs in the bone marrow.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased margination of neutrophils along vessel walls\u003C/strong\u003E - Inflammation actually increases margination and adhesion of neutrophils to endothelium as part of the inflammatory response.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith prolonged infection, there is also increased production of colony-stimulating factors (CSFs) from activated macrophages and marrow stromal cells, which induces proliferation of leukocyte precursors in the bone marrow. This helps compensate for the loss of leukocytes in the inflammatory reaction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Leukocytosis is a common feature of inflammatory reactions, especially in bacterial infections, with white cell counts typically rising to 15,000-20,000 cells/mL.","Extreme leukocytosis (40,000-100,000 cells/mL) is called a leukemoid reaction and must be distinguished from leukaemia.","Bacterial infections typically cause neutrophilia, viral infections cause lymphocytosis, and allergies and helminth infestations cause eosinophilia."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 102"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77575"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20681"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77575"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-24T12:50:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-24T12:52:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13557"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94535"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation 